&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;52nd Amendment Act&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The 52nd Amendment Act of 1985 added the 10th Schedule to the Indian Constitution.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The 10th Schedule is commonly known as the Anti-Defection Law.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Anti-Defection Law lays down the process by which legislators may be disqualified on grounds of defection.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This amendment aimed to address the issue of political defections by legislators, which were becoming a common problem in Indian politics.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Defection:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Defection refers to the act of a member of a legislative body leaving their political party to join another.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Anti-Defection Law was introduced to prevent such political defections.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Disqualification:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The 10th Schedule outlines the grounds for disqualification of legislators on the grounds of defection.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A legislator can be disqualified if they voluntarily give up the membership of their party or disobey the party&amp;#39;s directives.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Exceptions:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The law allows for certain exceptions, such as mergers between parties.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If a party merges with another and two-thirds of its legislators agree, they are not considered to have defected.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Authority:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The presiding officer of the house (Speaker or Chairman) is the authority to decide on disqualification matters under the 10th Schedule.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;However, the decision of the presiding officer is subject to judicial review.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;56 and 30.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

